nese, Irish and Jewish diasporic communities. By turning the spotlight on Manchester’s rich, yet under-represented, literary tradition in this way, Postcolonial Manchester also argues for the devolution of the canon of English Literature and, in particular, recognition for contemporary black and Asian literary culture outside of London.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEnglish literaturezEnglandzManchesterxMinority authors. 0aImmigrants' writings, EnglishzEnglandzManchesterxHistory and criticism. 4aLiterature Studies 2020. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh  aAsian poet.  aLemn Sissay.  aPostcolonial Manchester.  aSuAndi.  ablack poet.  acollective resistance.  acrime capital.  adiaspora space.  aliterary culture.  amixed-genre anthologies.  apublishing houses.  ashort story.1 aCrawshaw, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrawshaw, Robert, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFowler, Corinne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFowler, Corinne, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPearce, Lynne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPearce, Lynne, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152610188440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526101884423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526101884/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles